result.execSummary:
The defendant Antoine D Curry was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case.

  • Disorderly Conduct [Modifiers: Repeater], a class B misdemeanor, Wisconsin Statutes 947.01(1).
  • Resisting or Obstructing an Officer [Modifiers: Repeater], a class A misdemeanor, Wisconsin Statutes 946.41(1).

Charge(s) in this case were read in to this or other case(s). A "read in" charge is a charge that is dismissed as part of a plea agreement, however:

  • The defendant agrees to have the court consider the charge(s) when sentencing for another crime, under Wis. Stats. 973.20(1g)(b); and
  • The defendant cannot be prosecuted for these charge(s) in the future.

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

COPY IN FILE

Defendant Antoine D Curry in court with attorney Daniel E Meylink.  Defendant Antoine D Curry in custody.  William P. Dockry appeared for the State of Wisconsin.  Deputy Court Clerk ssm.

AS TO COUNT 2:  Pursuant to plea negotiations and on motion of the State, Court orders count dismissed and read-in.

AS TO COUNTS 1 AND 3:  Defendant changes his plea to GUILTY.  Defendant examined as to his plea, advised of his Constitutional rights and the maximum penalty.   Defendant advised that if not a United States Citizen, deportation is possible.  Court found that defendant knowingly, voluntarily and intelligently waived his rights.  Guilty Plea Questionnaire/Waiver of Rights and Addendum received and filed.  Parties stipulate to the complaint as a factual basis to sustain defendant's plea.  Court found defendant guilty and ordered a Judgment of Conviction be entered on the record.  

Sentencing proceeded.  Statements by the State, defense and defendant.  Court sentenced defendant to serve 153 DAYS in the House of Correction CONCURRENT to each other with credit for 153 days served FOR A TIME SERVED DISPOSITION.  

Court orders the defendant to submit a DNA sample but waives the DNA surcharge because it was previously paid.

AS TO COUNT 1 ONLY:  Court ordered defendant to pay a FINE of $150.00 INCLUDING ALL COSTS and SURCHARGES by 10/02/2017 or, as a penalty if not paid, convert to a civil judgment.  
Notice of Right to Seek Postconviction Relief received and filed.

AS TO COUNT 3 ONLY:  Court waives all costs and surcharges because it was ordered on Count 1 and due to the defendant's inability to pay.
